snippet.textDisplay:
It still, 4 days afterward, doesn’t seem real. I feel like I’m having some kind of nightmare dissociative episode or something. This person I’m watching right now is... not alive. It’s like I get it, but at the same time, I don’t. It’s somehow different than with, say, seeing Rod Serling narrate an old Twilight Zone episode. I can totally wrap my brain around the fact he’s dead. This, though... it just doesn’t add up somehow.
I heard Colin Cowherd say something interesting: at the moment Kobe retired, he had been an NBA player for more of his life (~20 years) than he hadn’t (~17-18). Even now, him being a celebrity and public icon vs. not is pretty darn close. So this person we’ve pretty much all known for the majority of his life is... gone. Hits REALLY hard, even to someone who wasn’t even really an NBA fan, much less a Laker fan.

snippet.textDisplay: He saved my life. He is my hero. When I was a teenager, moving from Brazil to US and trying to fit in was hard. I didn’t speak English at all and also never played basketball in my life. I never got a chance to watch a basketball game in Brazil because we grew up in a humble home. As I finally got to watch the lakers.. it was exactly when Kobe was a young kid coming into the NBA. I was bullied so much so sucking at basketball in 8th grade as it was my first time ever playing. I remember hearing Kobe saying something like.. don’t let anyone tell you that you can’t do something that you love “just do it”. I was in deep depression at that time.. with thoughts of suicide. That message changed me. I worked so hard on my English, I worked super hard in learning how to play basketball. Learning how to dribble, how to be super athletic because I figure that was my chance to make the 8th grade team. As I learned basketball I was able to start in the varsity team my high school years. I got to a point where I could play D2 or CC basketball. I chose to go run track and field at BYU on a scholarship. I know that through the grit that I learned from Kobe Bryant, I was able to learn the things I learned and become a college athlete. I was able to get my degree and today I have a family. I am happy. I love my life. I thank Kobe for unintentionally saving my life when I was only 14 years old. RIP Kobe
